    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Sparks From a Debate, in New York and Beyond</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alma Graham letter hopes that female voters in New York remember how Rick Lazio belligerently pushed document in Hillary Clinton's face during campaign debate (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Fierce Opening Debate'' (editorial, Sept. 14):</p>
        <p>In commenting on the debate between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Representative Rick A. Lazio, you assert that Mr. Lazio ''scored the evening's theatrical coup when he approached his opponent's lectern and dared her to sign a pledge to swear off soft money.''</p>
        <p>Mr. Lazio's action, in which he brandished a document like a weapon, looked very different to women than to men. This is a prime example of a woman's space being invaded by a belligerent man. Mrs. Clinton is to be commended for holding her ground. I hope that every female voter in New York State will remember Mr. Lazio's bullying behavior when she enters the voting booth.</p>
        <p>ALMA GRAHAM  New York, Sept. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
